@Francis, I’m sure someone who is more musically inclined can answer better, but from what I understand, the C-Clef on the third line of the staff is the Alto Clef. There are only a handful of instruments that use the clef for their notation, mainly viola and viola-like instruments and the alto trombone. 

The other two clefs are much more common, the treble for most instruments (like the violin, guitar, oboes, saxophones, etc), and the bass for lower pitched instruments (like the cello, bass guitar, or tuba).

The bass and treble clefs cover musical tonal range pretty well, as pianists can attest, but I imagine using both clefs for a musical instrument that ranges from the mid range of the bass clef to the mid range of the treble can be awkward. So I think the alto clef is used to straddle the bass and treble clefs to make notation easier for instruments in that range.

